    </div>
    <p id="whyceno">
      Most circumvention systems face the proxy distribution problem - getting
      its address to the user before the censor updates their blocklists. By
      design, peer-to-peer networks have an advantage over this model with
      every participant acting as a proxy for someone else. The protocol can
      locate information anywhere on the network, without user knoweldge or
      intervention. CeNo on top of an existing P2P network called Freenet, an
      anonymous and highly encrypted network for file sharing and storage,
      designed for censorship resistance. CeNo allows users to request Web
      pages and store them in Freenet. Once a site has been insterted, it is
      accessible to every CeNo user.
    </p>
